	<h2>Public Programming</h2>
	<p>New York City subsidizes massive cultural programming during the summer months. Exploiting these resources allows you to experience premium entertainment without capital expenditure.</p>
	
	<h3>Central Park SummerStage</h3>
	<p>The City Parks Foundation hosts free concerts throughout the five boroughs, with the flagship venue located in Central Park. The programming spans indie rock, hip-hop, and classical music. Arrive at least two hours before the gates open for high-profile artists, as capacity is strictly enforced.</p>

	<h2>Film and Culture</h2>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Bryant Park Movie Nights:</strong> Every Monday evening, Bryant Park screens classic films on the lawn. The lawn opens at 5:00 PM. You must arrive exactly at 5:00 PM and sprint to secure a plot of grass for your blanket. It operates as a highly competitive land grab.</li>
		<li><strong>Museum Free Days:</strong> Major institutions offer free or pay-what-you-wish admission during specific windows. The Museum of Modern Art (MoMA) offers free admission on the first Friday evening of every month for NYC residents (use your sublet address). The Guggenheim offers pay-what-you-wish on Saturday evenings.</li>
		<li><strong>Shakespeare in the Park:</strong> The Public Theater stages free, high-production-value Shakespeare performances at the Delacorte Theater. Securing tickets requires joining a digital lottery or waiting in the physical standby line starting at 6:00 AM.</li>
	</ul>
</InternWiki>
